<h2 class="h5 mt-4">Overview</h2>
<p>
    This directed independent study examines how UNF's cybersecurity competition team prepares for competitions, where
    the current process breaks down, and what a more effective operating model could look like. The project combines
    current-state analysis, future-state process design, and an in-progress course design component intended to help
    strengthen long-term training and readiness.
</p>

<h2 class="h5 mt-4">Why It Matters</h2>
<p>
    Student competition teams often depend heavily on informal knowledge transfer, a small number of highly prepared
    members, and limited structured practice time. That makes performance inconsistent and makes it difficult to retain
    knowledge from one season to the next. This project treats those issues as process and training design problems,
    not just individual performance problems.
</p>

<h2 class="h5 mt-4">My Role</h2>
<p>
    I conducted the analysis for the study, documented the current preparation and competition workflow, and developed
    recommendations for improving training, readiness standards, and operational structure. I also produced the written
    deliverables for both the current-state findings and the future-state model.
</p>

<h2 class="h5 mt-4">Research and Analysis Approach</h2>
<p>
    The first phase focused on understanding the team's current process using questionnaire data and process analysis.
    The second phase translated those findings into a future-state model with practical recommendations that could improve
    readiness, continuity, and execution without depending on major new institutional support. A third phase is now in
    progress and is focused on outlining a possible penetration testing course by comparing study findings against
    existing course structure to determine what should be added, changed, or removed.
</p>

<h2 class="h5 mt-4">Deliverables</h2>
<h3 class="h6 mt-3">Deliverable 1: Current-State Analysis</h3>
<p>
    Documented how the team currently prepares, practices, and operates during competitions. This phase identified
    recurring weaknesses in readiness, workflow discipline, simulation frequency, and knowledge continuity.
</p>

<h3 class="h6 mt-3">Deliverable 2: Future-State Model and Recommendations</h3>
<p>
    Proposed a revised operating model focused on year-round continuity, more realistic practice structure, clearer
    operational roles, stronger readiness expectations, and better process control during competition scenarios.
</p>

<h3 class="h6 mt-3">Deliverable 3: Course Design Proposal (In Progress)</h3>
<p>
    In progress. This deliverable is focused on building a class outline for a possible penetration testing course
    using study findings and an existing networking course syllabus as a baseline for evaluating what should be added,
    changed, or removed.
</p>

<h2 class="h5 mt-4">Key Findings</h2>
<p>
    The current-state analysis showed that preparation was limited in both frequency and depth, with readiness
    concentrated in a relatively small portion of the team. It also identified weak points in competition workflow,
    including response and recovery practice, change tracking, prioritization under pressure, and broader operational
    consistency across members.
</p>

<h2 class="h5 mt-4">Proposed Improvements</h2>
<p>
    The future-state model recommends a more continuous and structured approach to team development. Key areas include
    stronger leadership continuity, more realistic simulation-based practice, clearer operational roles during
    competition, stronger readiness checkpoints, and improved documentation and change-control discipline.
</p>

<h2 class="h5 mt-4">Current Status</h2>
<p>
    Deliverables 1 and 2 are complete. Deliverable 3 is still in development and will be added to this project page
    once the course outline is finished.
</p>

<h2 class="h5 mt-4">Artifacts</h2>
<p>
    This page can include selected excerpts from the written deliverables, such as charts, process diagrams, readiness
    frameworks, recommendation summaries, and other supporting materials that show how the analysis was performed and
    what was proposed.
</p>

